"'''True Tears of Joy'''" was the fourth single from Australian [[Pub rock (Australia)|pub rockers]], [[Hunters & Collectors]]' seventh studio album, ''[[Cut (Hunters and Collectors album)|Cut]]''. It was released after the album on 23 November 1992.<ref name=ariareport/> It peaked at No.&nbsp;14 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] – the highest charting single of their career – and No.&nbsp;47 on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Singles Chart]]. "True Tears of Joy" was co-written by band members John Archer, Doug Falconer, Jack Howard, Robert Miles, [[Barry Palmer (musician)|Barry Palmer]], [[Mark Seymour]], [[Jeremy Smith (Australian musician)|Jeremy Smith]], and Michael Waters.

== Background ==

Australian pub rockers [[Hunters & Collectors]] released "True Tears of Joy" on 23 November 1992<ref name=ariareport/> a month after their seventh studio album,<ref name="Holmgren"/><ref name="Relph"/> ''[[Cut (Hunters and Collectors album)|Cut]]'', which was issued in October.<ref name="McFarlane"/><ref name="Nimmervoll"/> The track was co-written by band members John Archer on bass guitar, Doug Falconer on drums, Jack Howard on trumpet, Robert Miles on live sound, [[Barry Palmer (musician)|Barry Palmer]] on guitar, [[Mark Seymour]] on lead vocals, [[Jeremy Smith (Australian musician)|Jeremy Smith]] on French horn, and Michael Waters on keyboards and trombone.<ref name="Holmgren"/><ref name="McFarlane"/><ref name="APRA True Tears"/>

"True Tears of Joy" was released as a CD single on White Label/[[Mushroom Records]] and, as with the album, was co-produced by [[Don Gehman]] and Hunters & Collectors, with Rick Will as the assistant producer.<ref name="Holmgren"/><ref name="Relph"/> The single reached No.&nbsp;14 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] and although it did not enter the top&nbsp;50 until February 1993 it became the highest charting single of their career.<ref name="AusCharts"/> It peaked No.&nbsp;47 on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Singles Chart]].<ref name="NZL Charts"/>

In the liner notes for the band's compilation album, ''Natural Selection'', Seymour provides the following description for the song; "She's standing at the gate about to depart for Tokyo to pursue dubious employment. She doesn't want to go, doesn't know why she's going, runs off... tears streaming down her face. Hardly joyous. That came later."<ref name="Natural Selection"/>

Seymour provided an acoustic version for his fourth solo album, ''[[Daytime and the Dark]]'', which was released in May 2005. A cover version of "True Tears of Joy" by [[Paul Kelly (Australian musician)|Paul Kelly]] with [[Emma Donovan]] and [[Jimblah]] was included on the 2013 tribute album, ''Crucible – The Songs of Hunters & Collectors''.<ref name ="Zuel"/><ref name="Triple M"/> Kelly commented that the artists, Donovan and Jimblah, that he recorded the track with in the previous November, together with the producers, Tim Levinson ([[Urthboy]]) and Angus Stuart ([[Hermitude|El Gusto]]) were "a good little team all in one room" .<ref name="Kelly"/>

== Reception ==

Bevan Hannan of ''[[The Canberra Times]]'' in a review of ''Cut'' describes how "Mark Seymour is also in excellent form up-front, mainly in the ballads, with 'True Tears of Joy' a real beauty".<ref name="Hannan"/>

